HOUSE RESOLUTION NO. 348
BY REPRESENTATIVE WALTERS
A RESOLUTION
To create a subcommittee to be comprised of members of the House Committee on
Commerce to study whether persons working as funeral planners, funeral arrangers,
end-of-life doulas, death doulas, or under any similar designation should be subject
to state regulation, credentialing, and oversight, and to make recommendations for
policy and legislative changes on or before November 1, 2026.
WHEREAS, demand for paid funeral planning and end-of-life doula services has
expanded rapidly in recent years, while no state in the United States currently requires
government licensure or certification to practice as a funeral planner or an end-of-life doula,
and the most prominent national organization in the field, the National End-of-Life Doula
Alliance, offers only a voluntary proficiency credential and does not accredit or evaluate any
training program; and
WHEREAS, the absence of any state credentialing, bonding, or licensure requirement
for persons offering paid funeral planning or end-of-life doula services in this state creates
risks for licensed funeral directors and funeral homes, including the receipt of undisclosed
referral fees or insurance commissions, the unauthorized acceptance of consumer payments
for goods or services to be delivered upon death, exposure of licensed funeral establishments
to civil liability arising from the acts of unlicensed third parties, and consumer confusion
regarding qualifications and accountability, all of which warrant further study.
WHEREAS, this state licenses funeral directors, embalmers, funeral establishments,
and crematory authorities through the Louisiana State Board of Embalmers and Funeral
Directors pursuant to R.S. 37:831 et seq.; regulates cemeteries through the Louisiana
Cemetery Board pursuant to Title 8 of the Louisiana Revised Statutes of 1950; restricts the
entering into of preneed funeral contracts to duly licensed funeral establishments pursuant
to R.S. 37:861; and prohibits funeral establishments and their agents from using "cappers,
steerers, or runners" and from soliciting, accepting, or paying consideration for
recommending a provider of funeral goods and services pursuant to R.S. 37:846(A)(3), but
