does not define, license, register, or set qualifications for persons offering paid funeral
planning or end-of-life doula services as a profession; and
THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the Legislature of Louisiana does hereby
establish and provide for a subcommittee of the House Committee on Commerce to study
and recommend legislation, administrative rules, or other measures concerning the
regulation, credentialing, and oversight of persons offering paid funeral planning, and may
propose recommendations, together with specific proposals for legislation, and to make
recommendations on or before November 1, 2026, unless the chair of the subcommittee
determines additional time is needed. Any recommendations or proposals shall be submitted
by written report to the legislature and to the David R. Poynter Legislative Research Library
as required by R.S. 24:771 and 772.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the legislature recommends that the
subcommittee include consideration of all of the following:
(1) Whether terms such as "funeral planner", "death doula", and related designations
ought to be defined in law, the appropriate scope of practice for each, and any necessary
exemptions for clergy, hospice workers, or volunteers.
(2) Whether such persons should be subject to licensure, registration, certification,
bonding, or other credentialing, and the minimum education, training, examination, and
continuing education standards appropriate to the profession.
(3) Whether a prohibition of undisclosed finder's fees, commissions, or other
arrangements with licensed funeral establishments, cemetery authorities, crematories, or
insurers; or restrictions on the handling of consumer funds and insurance products marketed
in connection with funeral planning, consistent with R.S. 37:846, or with R.S. 37:861
through R.S. 37:866, and any other applicable provisions of the law and administrative codes
of this state; ought to be enacted.
(4) Contractual disclosure, transparency, and right-of-cancellation requirements, and
whether a consumer complaint, investigation, and disciplinary process is warranted,
including civil penalties and grounds for denial, suspension, or revocation of any license.
(5) The allocation of civil and criminal liability between licensed funeral
establishments and unlicensed funeral planners or end-of-life doulas, and any necessary safe
harbor or due diligence framework for licensed establishments interacting with such persons.
